Initial XGBoost¶

In [7]:
train.columns = train.columns.astype(str)
X = (train.iloc[:, :-1]
     .merge(pd.get_dummies(train["64"], prefix='64', drop_first=True),
           left_index=True,
           right_index=True)
         .drop(columns = ['64']))
y = train.iloc[:, -1].values

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X.values, y, test_size=0.33, stratify=y)

X_train_df = (pd.DataFrame(X_train, columns = X.columns)
             .astype(int))
X_test_df = (pd.DataFrame(X_test, columns = X.columns)
            .astype(int))
In [9]:
model = xgboost.XGBClassifier(
 objective= 'multi:softmax',
    num_class= 4,
 seed=27)
model.fit(X_train_df, y_train);
In [11]:
y_pred = model.predict(X_test_df)
print(accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred))
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred))

In [12]:
validate = pd.read_csv("test.csv", header=None)
validate.columns = validate.columns.astype(str)
validate = validate.fillna(validate.mean())

X_val = (validate.iloc[:, :-1]
     .merge(pd.get_dummies(validate["64"], prefix='64', drop_first=True),
           left_index=True,
           right_index=True)
         .drop(columns = ['64'])
        )
y_val = validate.iloc[:, -1].values
y_val_pred = model.predict(X_val)
print(classification_report(y_val, y_val_pred))

              precision    recall  f1-score   support

Does perfectly on a small test set, but about equal to chance on the actual validation set. Must be overfitting! I'll do some hyperparameter tuning with the parameters that can help that.

Hyperparameter Optimization¶

Did some grid searching, and found this

In [14]:
model = xgboost.XGBClassifier(
    n_estimators=1000,
 learning_rate =0.01,
 max_depth=8,
 objective= 'multi:softmax',
    num_class= 4,
    subsample = 0.05,
    colsample_bytree = 0.001,
#    eval_set= [(X_val_df, y_val)],
 seed=27)
model.fit(X, y);

y_val_pred = model.predict(X_val)
print(classification_report(y_val, y_val_pred))

              precision    recall  f1-score   support

           0       0.94      0.93      0.94       712
           1       0.85      0.99      0.91       777
           2       0.92      0.89      0.91       777
           3       0.88      0.77      0.82       734

    accuracy                           0.90      3000
   macro avg       0.90      0.89      0.89      3000
weighted avg       0.90      0.90      0.89      3000

Much better! Seems like it's underpredicting Class 3 and overpredicting Class 1, though. Maybe some Feature Selection could take care of that!

Feature Selection¶

In [15]:
explainer = shap.TreeExplainer(model)
shap_values = explainer.shap_values(X_val)
shap.summary_plot(shap_values, X_val)

Looks like column 47 isn't contributing much to the accuracy score, is increasing the odds of predicting Class 1 and very little to class 3. Maybe removing that would help!

In [16]:
X_mod = X.drop(columns = ["47"])
X_val_mod = X_val.drop(columns = ["47"])
model = xgboost.XGBClassifier(
    n_estimators=1000,
 learning_rate =0.01,
 max_depth=8,
 objective= 'multi:softmax',
    num_class= 4,
    subsample = 0.05,
    colsample_bytree = 0.001,
    eval_set= [(X_val_mod, y_val)],
 seed=27)
model.fit(X_mod, y);
explainer = shap.TreeExplainer(model)
shap_values = explainer.shap_values(X_val_mod)
shap.summary_plot(shap_values, X_val_mod)
y_val_pred = model.predict(X_val_mod)
print(classification_report(y_val, y_val_pred))

              precision    recall  f1-score   support

           0       0.95      0.95      0.95       712
           1       0.86      0.99      0.92       777
           2       0.94      0.91      0.93       777
           3       0.90      0.78      0.84       734

    accuracy                           0.91      3000
   macro avg       0.91      0.91      0.91      3000
weighted avg       0.91      0.91      0.91      3000

Squeezed some more performance out of it!
